`scripts/` is the project's CI/build automation layer: Layer 1 static checks, firmware cross-compilation, doc/contract regeneration, and vendored-patch reapplication. Depending on this directory means invoking `ci.sh` (the sole authoritative list of what "Layer 1" means) or `build_firmware.sh` as entry points; individual check scripts are not meant to be composed elsewhere.

Two vendored C++ trees (javelin-steno, javelin-steno-pico) are gitignored and get re-patched after every clone/sync by `apply_javelin_ext_patch.sh` and `apply_javelin_steno_split_patch.sh`, both idempotent via marker-string checks and both consuming committed `.patch` files (`javelin_ext_pico.patch`, `javelin_steno_pico_split.patch`, `javelin_steno_split.patch`) that must be regenerated by hand if upstream drifts — the patch files and their applier scripts change together. `build_firmware.sh` orchestrates both patch scripts plus `cargo build-javelin` (dictionary codegen) plus cmake/toolchain build, and is the only script that runs the full chain end-to-end. `cpp_check.sh` is the differential test that actually executes the generated dictionary against the Rust reference, consuming headers that `build-javelin` must already have written to `out/` — it never invokes cargo itself, to avoid a target-lock deadlock when called from within `cargo test`.

`ci.sh` never short-circuits (`RUN` helper collects all failures via `OVERALL`) and calls four repo-local scripts by fixed relative path: `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `cycle_check.sh` — renaming any of these requires editing `ci.sh`. All grep-based checks (`no_allow_check.sh`, `retired_terms_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`) enumerate files via `git ls-files`, never a filesystem walk, to avoid `target/` and concurrent-write races, and emit `FAIL: path:line:...` lines matching ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser contract — this format is a shared invariant across all violation-reporting scripts. `gen_readme_architecture.sh` and `gen_tool_contracts.sh` share the same marker-delimited splice pattern (`BEGIN/END GENERATED ...` HTML comments, awk-based replace, `--write`/`--check` modes) for keeping generated doc blocks in sync with source of truth. `install-tools.sh` and `update-template.sh` layer: the latter calls the former mid-run after syncing it, and both assume `../CTX` as the default sibling tooling repo.